p008 , maziarr , hamedrad}@ucr.edu . Abstract Continuously recorded high-resolution waveform measurements provide rich information about fast power system dynamics. However, they require automated methods to identify events. This problem is addressed by developing a spectrogram-based framework to jointly detect, localize, and classify events in real-world continuously recorded waveforms at the terminal of an Inverter-Based Resource. We recast this problem as a temporal object detection problem on spectrogram images, as they capture the transient and harmonic signatures more explicitly than in raw waveform data. Each time-series waveform is transformed using the short-time Fourier transform, and the resulting per-channel spectrograms are stacked as a tensor for event detection. We benchmark this method against a detector operating directly on raw time-series measurements. Experiments on single-phase disturbances and three-phase faults demonstrate that the proposed spectrogram method consistently improves event detection, localization, and classification over the raw waveform baseline. Keywords: Continuously recorded waveforms, inverter-based resources, event detection, spectrogram, deep learning. I Introduction Modern power systems are going through a rapid transition driven by the growing integration of inverter-based resources (IBRs), renewables, and power-electronic loads. These resources introduce fast transients as well as harmonic emissions. Typical events include switching, oscillations, and incipient faults. These events are difficult to analyze, yet detecting them is valuable, as they can reveal early fault detection and help prevent permanent damage. Such dynamics can be captured by the Waveform Measurement Unit (WMU), which records voltage and current waveforms as continuous samples at kilohertz rates [ 11 ] . A practical monitoring system answers three questions: whether an event is present (detection), when it begins and ends (localization), and what type it is (classification). Answering these questions is challenging for two reasons. First, events are vastly outnumbered by normal operation, creating severe class imbalance. Second, many of these event signatures are usually small in magnitude. Thus, the harmonic and transient spectral content that distinguishes an event may remain implicit in the time-series representation. To bridge this gap, this paper proposes a spectrogram-based event detector. Each waveform channel is transformed into the time-frequency domain, so that the harmonic and transient components appear as explicit visual features rather than being latent in the raw time-series measurements. Related Work: Existing works for power system event detection can be broadly categorized into two classes: time-series based methods and frequency-based methods. The time-series methods flag an event when the signal amplitude departs from its expected behavior. These approaches monitor the RMS value or the peak magnitude of voltage and current, and declare an event when a threshold is exceeded [ 12 , 3 ] . Such rules are simple and widely used in power quality monitoring. However, events whose signatures are subtle in magnitude, such as incipient faults or low-level oscillations, are missed as noise [ 6 , 7 ] . In contrast, frequency-based methods leverage the spectral content of the waveform. The Fourier transform captures harmonic and inter-harmonic components, but discards the time information needed for localization. Time-frequency representations recover this timing. The STFT, wavelet transform, S S -transform and Hilbert transform have been used in power-quality analysis [ 16 , 5 , 4 , 17 ] . These representations make transient and harmonic signatures explicit and can capture events that remain invisible to purely amplitude-based schemes [ 2 ] . Recent work couples time-frequency features with learning-based classifiers, ranging from support vector machines [ 1 ] and decision trees [ 8 ] to convolutional neural networks applied directly to time-frequency images [ 18 ] . Most existing learning-based schemes treat detection, localization, and classification as separate stages. In contrast, we address all three tasks jointly. The proposed approach falls within the frequency-based category. Our formulation is inspired by object detection in computer vision, where single-stage detectors such as YOLO [ 13 ] and SSD [ 9 ] regress bounding boxes together with class labels and confidence scores, avoiding the region-proposal stage of two-stage detectors [ 14 ] . A similar philosophy underlies sound event detection, where events are localized in time on audio spectrograms [ 10 ] . Building on these ideas, we adopt an encoder-decoder U-Net architecture [ 15 ] that scores every temporal window for event presence and class label. Contributions. The main contributions of the paper are as follows. First, we recast the detection, temporal localization, and classification of events as a single temporal object-detection problem on spectrogram images. Second, we introduce an STFT-based log-spectrogram tensor representation that maps multi-channel waveform measurements into a form that can be used for image-based object detection. Third, we develop a U-Net detector that regresses normalized temporal bounding boxes together with a confidence score and a class label. Finally, we evaluate the proposed framework against a raw time-series baseline on both single-phase and three-phase event detection tasks. II Problem Formulation We consider the problem of detecting events in time-synchronized waveforms, localizing each event in time, and identifying its label directly from the raw waveforms. Let X j ∈ ℝ T j × C X_{j}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T_{j}\\times C} denote the j j -th waveform record in the dataset, X j = [ x j ​ [ 0 ] , … , x j ​ [ T j − 1 ] ] ⊤ ∈ ℝ T j × C , X_{j}=\\big[\\,x_{j}[0],\\dots,x_{j}[T_{j}-1]\\,\\big]^{\\!\\top}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T_{j}\\times C}, (1) where T j T_{j} is the number of samples in the record and C C is the number of channels. For a system with P P phases, each sample t ∈ { 0 , … , T j − 1 } t\\in\\{0,\\dots,T_{j}-1\\} stacks the per-phase voltage and current measurements, x j ​ [ t ] = ( v 1 ​ [ t ] , … , v P ​ [ t ] , i 1 ​ [ t ] , … , i P ​ [ t ] ) ⊤ ∈ ℝ C , C = 2 ​ P , x_{j}[t]=\\big(v_{1}[t],\\dots,v_{P}[t],\\,i_{1}[t],\\dots,i_{P}[t]\\big)^{\\!\\top}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{C},~~C=2P, so that the single-phase case corresponds to P = 1 P=1 ( C = 2 C=2 ) and the three-phase case to P = 3 P=3 ( C = 6 C=6 ). A record may contain one or more events. Each record is annotated with a set of E j E_{j} events, 𝒜 j = { ( I j , m , y j , m ) } m = 1 E j , \\mathcal{A}_{j}=\\big\\{\\,(I_{j,m},\\,y_{j,m})\\,\\big\\}_{m=1}^{E_{j}}, (2) where I j , m = [ s j , m , e j , m ] I_{j,m}=[\\,s_{j,m},\\,e_{j,m}\\,] , with 0 ≤ s j , m ≤ e j , m ≤ T j − 1 0\\leq s_{j,m}\\leq e_{j,m}\\leq T_{j}-1 , is the temporal interval (onset and offset samples) of the m m -th event, and y j , m ∈ 𝒴 y_{j,m}\\in\\mathcal{Y} is its class label. The label set 𝒴 = { 1 , … , K } \\mathcal{Y}=\\{\\,1,\\dots,K\\,\\} has K K event classes. Given a waveform record X X of length T T , our objective is to jointly detect, temporally localize, and classify the events it contains. We cast this as learning a detector f θ : ℝ T × C → 𝒟 f_{\\theta}:\\ \\mathbb{R}^{T\\times C}\\to\\mathcal{D} , parameterized by θ \\theta , that maps a record to an element of the space 𝒟 \\mathcal{D} of scored detection sets. Concretely, the detector returns a set of N ^ \\hat{N} candidate detections, f θ ​ ( ⋅ ) = { ( b ^ k , p ^ k , y ^ k ) } k = 1 N ^ , f_{\\theta}(\\cdot)=\\big\\{\\,(\\hat{b}_{k},\\ \\hat{p}_{k},\\ \\hat{y}_{k})\\,\\big\\}_{k=1}^{\\hat{N}}, (3) where b ^ k = [ s ^ k , e ^ k ] \\hat{b}_{k}=[\\,\\hat{s}_{k},\\,\\hat{e}_{k}\\,] is a predicted event interval, p ^ k ∈ [ 0 , 1 ] \\hat{p}_{k}\\in[0,1] is the confidence score of an event present in b ^ k \\hat{b}_{k} , and y ^ k ∈ 𝒴 \\hat{y}_{k}\\in\\mathcal{Y} is the predicted event class. A predicted detection is deemed correct when its temporal intersection-over-union (IoU) with a ground-truth interval of the same class meets or exceeds a preset threshold ( α ) (\\alpha) at inference. III Spectrogram Image Construction and Training Dataset In this section, we describe how each waveform record is mapped to a time-frequency spectrogram image and how the sample-level annotations in the waveform are converted into normalized temporal boxes used for training. III-A Spectrogram Image The STFT slides a short analysis window across each channel of the record. Each channel waveform is divided into short, overlapping frames of L L samples, where frame m m begins at sample m ​ H mH and the hop H = ( 1 − p / 100 ) ​ L H=(1-p/100)L is set by p % p\\% overlap between consecutive frames. For channel c c , the frame m m is the vector X c m ∈ ℝ L X_{c}^{\\,m}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{L} defined as X c m ​ [ n ] = x c ​ [ n + m ​ H ] , n = 0 , … , L − 1 , X_{c}^{\\,m}[n]=x_{c}[\\,n+mH\\,],\\qquad n=0,\\dots,L-1, (4) where x c ​ [ ⋅ ] x_{c}[\\cdot] denotes the c c -th channel of the record. A record of length T j T_{j} yields M j = ⌊ ( T j − L ) / H ⌋ + 1 M_{j}=\\big\\lfloor(T_{j}-L)/H\\big\\rfloor+1 frames, indexed m = 0 , … , M j − 1 m=0,\\dots,M_{j}-1 . Each frame in ( 4 ) is tapered by a smooth Hamming window g ​ [ n ] g[n] to limit spectral leakage and is mapped to a Q Q -point discrete Fourier transform (DFT), X ~ c m ​ ( f ) = ∑ n = 0 L − 1 g ​ [ n ] ​ X c m ​ [ n ] ​ e − ȷ ​ 2 ​ π ​ f ​ n / Q , f = 1 , … , Q − 1 , \\tilde{X}_{c}^{\\,m}(f)=\\sum_{n=0}^{L-1}g[n]\\,X_{c}^{\\,m}[n]\\,e^{-\\jmath 2\\pi fn/Q},\\quad f=1,\\dots,Q-1, (5) with Q ≥ L Q\\geq L . The corresponding power spectrum is P c m ​ ( f ) = 1 L ​ | X ~ c m ​ ( f ) | 2 . P_{c}^{\\,m}(f)=\\tfrac{1}{L}\\,\\big|\\tilde{X}_{c}^{\\,m}(f)\\big|^{2}. (6) Two further steps turn ( 6 ) into a suitable representation for detection. First, the diagnostic content is concentrated in the low-order harmonics, so of the Q Q DFT bins we retain only the F F lowest-frequency bins. The discarded bins carry mostly noise, and removing them reduces the input size and the computation. Second, the fundamental dominates the spectrum by several orders of magnitude; therefore, a logarithmic compression rescales faint harmonics so that they remain visible alongside the much stronger fundamental, S ~ c m ​ ( f ) = log ⁡ ( 1 + P c m ​ ( f ) ) , f = 1 , … , F . \\tilde{S}_{c}^{\\,m}(f)=\\log\\!\\big(1+P_{c}^{\\,m}(f)\\big),\\qquad f=1,\\dots,F. (7) Collecting ( 7 ) over all frames of a waveform yields the per-channel log-spectrogram, S c ∈ ℝ M j × F , [ S c ] m , f = S ~ c m ​ ( f ) . S_{c}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M_{j}\\times F},\\qquad\\big[S_{c}\\big]_{m,f}=\\tilde{S}_{c}^{\\,m}(f). (8) Finally, stacking ( 8 ) over the channel set 𝒞 \\mathcal{C} , produces a tensor, 𝐙 j = stack c ∈ 𝒞 ( S c ) ∈ ℝ M j × F × C , [ 𝐙 j ] m , f , c = S ~ c m ​ ( f ) , \\mathbf{Z}_{j}=\\operatorname*{stack}_{c\\in\\mathcal{C}}\\big(S_{c}\\big)\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M_{j}\\times F\\times C},\\quad\\big[\\mathbf{Z}_{j}\\big]_{m,f,c}=\\tilde{S}_{c}^{\\,m}(f), (9) which is the multi-channel spectrogram scene presented to the detector. Fig. 1 illustrates this construction. Figure 1: The figure shows the construction of the spectrogram tensor Z j Z_{j} used as training data. Panel (a) shows a STFT pipeline, illustrated on the phase voltage v a v_{a} . The waveform x ​ ( t ) x(t) is split into overlapping L L -sample frames at hop H H , each tapered by a Hamming window g g and mapped to its log-power spectrogram (Eqs. ( 4 )–( 7 )). Placing these vectors side by side for all m = 0 , … , M j − 1 m=0,\\dots,M_{j}-1 assembles the per-channel log-spectrogram S c S_{c} of Eq. ( 8 ). Panel (b) shows the per-channel log-spectrograms S c ∈ ℝ M j × F S_{c}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M_{j}\\times F} (Eq. ( 8 )) of all six channels of three-phase, stacked along the channel axis into the tensor 𝐙 j ∈ ℝ M j × F × 6 \\mathbf{Z}_{j}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M_{j}\\times F\\times 6} (Eq. ( 9 )), the input to the detector. III-B Training Dataset The frame m m spans samples [ m ​ H , m ​ H + L − 1 ] [mH,\\,mH+L-1] , so it overlaps the event if and only if m ​ H ≤ e mH\\leq e and m ​ H + L − 1 ≥ s mH+L-1\\geq s . Solving these two inequalities yields the event frame span, m s = ⌈ s − L + 1 H ⌉ , m e = ⌊ e H ⌋ . m_{s}=\\Big\\lceil\\tfrac{s-L+1}{H}\\Big\\rceil,\\qquad m_{e}=\\Big\\lfloor\\tfrac{e}{H}\\Big\\rfloor. (10) Since the detector localizes the event along the time-axis, the ground-truth fault box reduces to the frame interval ( m s , m e ) \\big(m_{s},\\,m_{e}\\big) . We express it in normalized form: b = ( t c , w t ) ∈ [ 0 , 1 ] 2 , t c = m s + m e 2 ​ M j , w t = m e − m s M j , b\\!=\\!\\big(t_{c},w_{t}\\big)\\in[0,1]^{2},\\quad t_{c}\\!=\\!\\frac{m_{s}+m_{e}}{2M_{j}},\\quad w_{t}\\!=\\!\\frac{m_{e}-m_{s}}{M_{j}}, (11) and paired with the class label y j ∈ 𝒴 y_{j}\\in\\mathcal{Y} . Normalizing by the number of frames M j M_{j} makes the box coordinates independent of the record length and the chosen hop. The training set is then the collection of spectrogram scenes paired with their annotations 𝒟 = { ( 𝐙 j , { ( b j , m , y j , m ) } m = 1 E j ) } j , \\mathcal{D}=\\Big\\{\\,\\big(\\mathbf{Z}_{j},\\;\\{(b_{j,m},y_{j,m})\\}_{m=1}^{E_{j}}\\big)\\,\\Big\\}_{j}, (12) where ( b j , m , y j , m ) (b_{j,m},y_{j,m}) denotes the normalized box label pair of the m m -th event of record j j , so that it contains a box label pair per event and E j = 0 E_{j}=0 for records without events. IV Fault Detection Framework We now describe the detector that operates on the spectrogram scenes of Section III . Let f θ f_{\\theta} denote the U-Net detector that maps a scene 𝐙 j \\mathbf{Z}_{j} to a set of N ^ \\hat{N} candidate detections, f θ ​ ( 𝐙 j ) = { ( b ^ k , p ^ k , y ^ k ) } k = 1 N ^ , f_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{Z}_{j})=\\big\\{(\\hat{b}_{k},\\hat{p}_{k},\\hat{y}_{k})\\big\\}_{k=1}^{\\hat{N}}, (13) where b ^ k = ( t ^ c , w ^ t ) ∈ [ 0 , 1 ] 2 \\hat{b}_{k}=(\\hat{t}_{c},\\hat{w}_{t})\\in[0,1]^{2} is a predicted temporal box in normalized coordinates of ( 11 ), p ^ k ∈ [ 0 , 1 ] \\hat{p}_{k}\\in[0,1] its confidence score, and y ^ k \\hat{y}_{k} its predicted class. Inverting the normalization in ( 11 ) for a predicted event box b ^ = ( t ^ c , w ^ t ) \\hat{b}=(\\hat{t}_{c},\\hat{w}_{t}) gives the frame interval: m ^ s = ⌊ M j ​ ( t ^ c − w ^ t 2 ) ⌋ , m ^ e = ⌈ M j ​ ( t ^ c + w ^ t 2 ) ⌉ , \\hat{m}_{s}=\\Big\\lfloor M_{j}\\big(\\hat{t}_{c}-\\tfrac{\\hat{w}_{t}}{2}\\big)\\Big\\rfloor,\\qquad\\hat{m}_{e}=\\Big\\lceil M_{j}\\big(\\hat{t}_{c}+\\tfrac{\\hat{w}_{t}}{2}\\big)\\Big\\rceil, (14) giving estimated event interval [ s ^ , e ^ ] = [ m ^ s ​ H , m ^ e ​ H + L − 1 ] [\\hat{s},\\hat{e}]=[\\hat{m}_{s}H,\\hat{m}_{e}H+L-1] . IV-A Training the U-Net Detector We train the network for detection and classification simultaneously. The detection objective applies to every temporal window and uses a class-weighted cross-entropy loss function, assigning a higher weight to event windows to compensate for their scarcity relative to normal operation. The classification objective applies only to event-containing windows and uses cross-entropy loss over the event classes. The overall objective is: ℒ = ℒ detection + ℒ classification \\mathcal{L}=\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{detection}}+\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{classification}} . The network learns to assign each window a confidence score, i.e., the probability that an event is present in that window. IV-B Selecting Candidates via the Confidence Threshold τ \\tau At inference, among the N ^ \\hat{N} candidates in ( 13 ) we retain those whose confidence satisfies p ^ k ≥ τ \\hat{p}_{k}\\geq\\tau . If no candidate survives, the scene is declared event-free. The threshold τ \\tau is chosen by the validation set. We compute the precision and recall for each τ \\tau , and select the value that maximizes their F ​ 1 F1 score. The selected τ \\tau is then fixed for all test records. IV-C Evaluation metrics We consider different evaluation metrics for detection, localization, and classification: Localization It is evaluated using intersection-over-union (IoU) between a predicted b ^ \\hat{b} and a true interval b b , IoU ​ ( b ^ , b ) = | b ^ ∩ b | | b ^ ∪ b | , \\mathrm{IoU}(\\hat{b},b)=\\frac{|\\hat{b}\\cap b|}{|\\hat{b}\\cup b|}, (15) where | ⋅ | |\\cdot| denotes the length of the interval. We report the IoU of the matched detections, averaged over the test events. Detection At a fixed overlap threshold α \\alpha , a predicted interval counts as a true positive (TP) if IoU ​ ( b ^ , b ) ≥ α \\mathrm{IoU}(\\hat{b},b)\\geq\\alpha ; any other predicted interval is a false positive (FP), and a ground-truth event with no matching prediction is a false negative (FN). Then, precision and recall are P = TP TP + FP , R = TP TP + FN . P=\\frac{\\mathrm{TP}}{\\mathrm{TP}+\\mathrm{FP}},\\qquad R=\\frac{\\mathrm{TP}}{\\mathrm{TP}+\\mathrm{FN}}. (16) Varying the confidence threshold τ \\tau at fixed α \\alpha traces a precision-recall curve. We define the average precision as AP = ∑ n ( R n + 1 − R n ) ​ P interp ​ ( R n + 1 ) , P interp ​ ( R ) = max R ~ ≥ R ⁡ P ​ ( R ~ ) , \\displaystyle\\begin{aligned} &\\mathrm{AP}=\\sum_{n}\\big(R_{n+1}-R_{n}\\big)\\,P_{\\mathrm{interp}}(R_{n+1}),\\\\ &P_{\\mathrm{interp}}(R)=\\max_{\\tilde{R}\\geq R}P(\\tilde{R}),\\end{aligned} (17) i.e., the area under the interpolated precision-recall curve. With multiple event classes, we report the mean average precision mAP = 1 | 𝒴 | ​ ∑ i ∈ 𝒴 AP i \\mathrm{mAP}=\\tfrac{1}{|\\mathcal{Y}|}\\sum_{i\\in\\mathcal{Y}}\\mathrm{AP}_{i} . We also report mAP [ .5 : .95 ] \\mathrm{mAP}_{[.5:.95]} , obtained by averaging AP over the IoU thresholds α ∈ { 0.50 , 0.55 , … , 0.95 } \\alpha\\in\\{0.50,0.55,\\dots,0.95\\} . Classification The event type accuracy is computed on the true-positive detections. Among the correctly localized events, we report the fraction assigned the correct class label. TABLE I: Single-phase disturbance detection on the held-out test day ( 40 40 s of data), comparing the spectrogram U-Net-2D (ours) with the raw time-series U-Net-1D baseline across four STFT overlaps. Performance improves as the hop shrinks. Detection Localization Class. Representation Overlap (hop) AP@0.5 AP@0.7 mAP [.5:.95] Recall@0.5 IoU type accuracy time-series (baseline) — 0.650 0.550 0.650 0.831 0.654 0.454 spectrogram (ours) 0 % 0\\% ( H = 64 H{=}64 ) 0.949 0.705 0.950 0.796 0.974 0.557 spectrogram (ours) 25 % 25\\% ( H = 48 H{=}48 ) 0.975 0.891 0.975 0.855 0.974 0.723 spectrogram (ours) 50 % 50\\% ( H = 32 H{=}32 ) 1.000 1.000 1.000 0.898 0.975 0.813 spectrogram (ours) 75 % 75\\% ( H = 16 H{=}16 ) 1.000 0.985 1.000 0.941 0.975 0.904 Figure 2: The figure shows a representative example of single-phase disturbance classes. The left panel shows the raw waveform with shaded event intervals and the right panel shows the corresponding spectrogram at 75 % 75\\% overlap ( L = 64 L{=}64 , H = 16 H{=}16 , F = 24 F{=}24 ). The harmonic distortion excites the odd harmonic bands, the interharmonics adds non-integer frequency bands, voltage flicker changes the fundamental into close sidebands, and the oscillatory transients have high frequency bands. Figure 3: The figure shows an event-level detection performance on the single-phase test day. Left panel shows precision-recall curve at fixed IoU threshold of 0.5 0.5 , comparing the time-series U-Net-1D with the spectrogram U-Net-2D under four STFT overlaps ( 0 % 0\\% , 25 % 25\\% , 50 % 50\\% , and 75 % 75\\% , with hop H ∈ { 64 , 48 , 32 , 16 } H\\in\\{64,48,32,16\\} ). Right panel shows the average precision (AP) as the IoU threshold is varied from 0.5 0.5 to 0.95 0.95 . The spectrogram variants outperform the time-series baseline, with performance improving with overlaps. V Experiments We now evaluate the proposed framework on two tasks: single-phase disturbance detection and three-phase fault detection at the terminal of an IBR. In both, we compare the detectors that differ only in their input representations. The baseline U-Net-1D takes raw 1D time-series signals, while the proposed U-Net-2D takes the stacked log-spectrogram tensor of Eq. ( 9 ). For both tasks, we use three-down encoder and three-up encoder with skip connections and channel widths ( 8 , 16 , 32 , 64 ) (8,16,32,64) , trained to jointly detect, localize and classify the events. The decision threshold τ \\tau is selected from the validation data as described in section IV . Performance is evaluated using IoU (Eq. ( 15 )), precision and recall (Eq. ( 16 )), AP at IoU thresholds α ∈ { 0.5 , 0.7 } \\alpha\\in\\{0.5,0.7\\} (Eq. ( 17 )), mAP [.5:.95] and event-type accuracy over true-positive detections with IoU ≥ 0.5 \\,\\geq 0.5 . The open source dataset and code repository are available at: https://github.com/shivanshutripath/Spectrogram-Based-Temporal-Event-Detection . V-A Single-phase disturbance detection We consider single-phase voltage and current waveforms ( P = 1 P=1 , C = 2 C=2 ) sampled at f s = 3000 f_{s}=3000 Hz over six independent days with 40 40 seconds of data per day at the terminal of an IBR. The data consists of multiple short disturbances of intervals [ s , e ] [s,e] , belonging to one of four classes: harmonic distortion, inter-harmonic distortion, voltage flicker, and oscillatory transients. The U-Net-1D operates directly on the time-series waveform, while the U-Net-2D operates on the corresponding spectrogram, computed with a Hamming window of length L = 64 L=64 , retaining the lowest F = 24 F=24 bins, at overlaps p ∈ { 0 , 25 , 50 , 75 } % p\\in\\{0,25,50,75\\}\\% . We use days 1 1 - 3 3 for training, days 4 4 - 5 5 for validation, and day 6 6 for testing. Both representations for an example of each disturbance class, are shown in Fig. 2 . Table I and Fig. 3 summarize the results. We observe that the spectrogram improves detection, localization, and classification at every overlap. The precision-recall curves in Fig. 3 (left) show the spectrogram near-unity precision, while the baseline degrades. In addition, the spectrogram achieves an IoU of 0.975 0.975 , against 0.654 0.654 for the baseline. Type-accuracy improves monotonically from 0.557 0.557 to 0.904 0.904 , compared to the baseline accuracy of 0.454 0.454 . Fig. 3 (right) shows that as the IoU threshold tightens toward 0.95 0.95 , the AP decays faster for the baseline than the spectrogram variants. V-B Three-phase fault detection We consider a three-phase dataset ( P = 3 P=3 , C = 6 C=6 ) recorded at the IBR terminal. Each record is a six-channel recording of voltages and currents ( V a , V b , V c , I a , I b , I c ) (V_{a},V_{b},V_{c},I_{a},I_{b},I_{c}) . The dataset comprises 200 200 recordings, sampled at f s = 1000 f_{s}=1000 Hz for 60 60 s, so 𝐗 ∈ ℝ T × 6 \\mathbf{X}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T\\times 6} with T = 60 , 000 T=60{,}000 . Each record carries a single fault from one of four classes: (i) single-line-to-ground, (ii) line-to-line, (iii) line-to-line-to-ground, and (iv) three-phase, annotated by its start and end ( s , e ) (s,e) . Each record is tagged with one of the two recording backgrounds { A , B } \\{A,B\\} that differ in noise conditions. We use 100 100 events for training and 34 34 for validation, both drawn from the background A A , and 66 66 events from the unseen background B B for testing, so the reported results also measure generalization across noise. The spectrogram is the per-channel log-STFT of Eqs. ( 5 )-( 9 ), computed with a Hamming window of length L = 64 L=64 . We vary the STFT overlap in four settings: (i) 0 % 0\\% overlap (hop H = 64 H=64 ) giving M = 937 M=937 frames, (ii) 25 % 25\\% overlap (hop H = 48 H=48 ) giving M = 1249 M=1249 frames, (iii) 50 % 50\\% overlap (hop H = 32 H=32 ) giving M = 1874 M=1874 frames, and (iv) 75 % 75\\% overlap (hop H = 16 H=16 ) giving M = 3747 M=3747 frames. In each case, we retain the lowest F = 24 F=24 bins, giving Z ∈ ℝ M × 24 × 6 Z\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M\\times 24\\times 6} . Table II and Fig. 4 summarize the results on the 66 66 test events. At 75 % 75\\% overlap, detection improves the baseline, with mAP [ .5 : .95 ] \\mathrm{mAP}_{[.5:.95]} rising from 0.655 0.655 to 0.858 0.858 , and Recall @ ​ 0.5 @0.5 increasing from 0.82 0.82 to 0.98 0.98 . The spectrogram IoU is slightly lower in 0 % 0\\% overlap but exceeds the baseline in finer hops, reaching 0.926 0.926 in 75 % 75\\% . Fault-type classification has accuracy 0.32 0.32 - 0.39 0.39 , yet consistently outperforms the baseline of 0.24 0.24 . Figure 4: The figure shows the fault-level detection performance of the U-Net on the 66 66 three-phase test events. The left panel shows the precision-recall curve at a fixed temporal-IoU threshold of 0.5 0.5 ; the raw time-series U-Net-1D (dashed gray) is compared with the spectrogram U-Net-2D under four STFT overlaps ( 0 % 0\\% , 25 % 25\\% , 50 % 50\\% , and 75 % 75\\% , with hop H ∈ { 64 , 48 , 32 , 16 } H\\in\\{64,48,32,16\\} ). The right panel shows the average precision (AP) as the IoU threshold is varied from 0.5 0.5 to 0.95 0.95 . Finer hops extend recall while maintaining high precision, the gap between the spectrogram and time-series curves widens at stricter thresholds, and performance improves with overlap. TABLE II: Three-phase fault detection on the 66 66 test events from the unseen background B B , comparing the spectrogram U-Net-2D (ours) with the raw time-series U-Net-1D baseline across four STFT overlaps. Performance improves as the hop shrinks. Detection Localization Class. Representation Overlap (hop) AP@0.5 AP@0.7 mAP [.5:.95] Recall@0.5 IoU type accuracy time-series (baseline) — 0.818 0.797 0.655 0.82 0.905 0.24 spectrogram (ours) 0 % 0\\% ( H = 64 H{=}64 ) 0.831 0.733 0.569 0.83 0.839 0.36 spectrogram (ours) 25 % 25\\% ( H = 48 H{=}48 ) 0.888 0.800 0.619 0.89 0.853 0.39 spectrogram (ours) 50 % 50\\% ( H = 32 H{=}32 ) 0.905 0.883 0.680 0.98 0.844 0.32 spectrogram (ours) 75 % 75\\% ( H = 16 H{=}16 ) 0.985 0.969 0.858 0.98 0.926 0.38 VI Conclusions This paper presented a spectrogram-based framework for the joint detection, localization, and classification of power system events from continuous waveform measurements at the terminal of an IBR. By transforming multi-channel waveforms into time-frequency representations and formulating the problem as temporal object detection, the proposed approach effectively captures transient and harmonic characteristics that are less apparent in raw time-series signals. The experimental results on single-phase and three-phase tasks show that the spectrogram representation consistently improves detection, localization, and event-type classification. Future work will focus on improving the results for event-type discrimination and extending the framework to real-time streaming operations. References [1] P. G. V. Axelberg, I. Y. Gu, and M. H. J. Bollen (2007) Support Vector Machine for Classification of Voltage Disturbances . IEEE Trans. on Power Delivery 22 ( 3 ), pp. 1297–1303 . Cited by: §I . [2] M. H. J. Bollen and I. Y. H. Gu (2006) Signal Processing of Power Quality Disturbances . Wiley-IEEE Press . Cited by: §I . [3] M. H. J. Bollen (2000) Understanding Power Quality Problems: Voltage Sags and Interruptions . IEEE Press , New York, NY . Cited by: §I . [4] P. K. Dash, B. K. Panigrahi, and G. Panda (2003) Power Quality Analysis Using S-Transform . IEEE Trans. on Power Delivery 18 ( 2 ), pp. 406–411 . Cited by: §I . [5] A. M. Gaouda, M. M. A. Salama, M. R. Sultan, and A. Y. Chikhani (1999) Power Quality Detection and Classification Using Wavelet-Multiresolution Signal Decomposition . IEEE Trans. on Power Delivery 14 ( 4 ), pp. 1469–1476 . Cited by: §I . [6] M. IzadI and H. Mohsenian-Rad (2022) A Synchronized Lissajous-Based Method to Detect and Classify Events in Synchro-Waveform Measurements in Power Distribution Networks . IEEE Trans. on Smart Grid 13 ( 3 ), pp. 2170–2184 . Cited by: §I . [7] M. Izadi and H. Mohsenian-Rad (2021) Synchronous Waveform Measurements to Locate Transient Events and Incipient Faults in Power Distribution Networks . IEEE Trans. on Smart Grid 12 ( 5 ), pp. 4295–4307 . Cited by: §I . [8] R. Kumar, B. Singh, D. T. Shahani, A. Chandra, and K. Al-Haddad (2015) Recognition of Power-Quality Disturbances Using S-Transform-Based ANN Classifier and Rule-Based Decision Tree . IEEE Trans. on Industry Applications 51 ( 2 ), pp. 1249–1258 . Cited by: §I . [9] W. Liu, D. Anguelov, D. Erhan, C. Szegedy, S. Reed, C. Fu, and A. C. Berg (2016) SSD: Single Shot MultiBox Detector . In Proc. of the European Conference on Computer Vision (ECCV) ,", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false, "persistedOutputPath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/718a8c7f-8b52-4dd6-87a7-df8e48076344/tool-results/bibhskr14.txt", "persistedOutputSize": 30432}}
