{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b9ccedbf7173b243", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tSpectrogram-Based Joint Detection, Localization, and Classification of Events in Continuously Recorded IBR Waveforms Report GitHub Issue × Title: Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: Description: Submit without GitHub Submit in GitHub arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! Learn more × Back to arXiv Why HTML? Report Issue Back to Abstract Download PDF Abstract I Introduction II Problem Formulation III Spectrogram Image Construction and Training Dataset III-A Spectrogram Image III-B Training Dataset IV Fault Detection Framework IV-A Training the U-Net Detector IV-B Selecting Candidates via the Confidence Threshold τ \\tau IV-C Evaluation metrics Localization Detection Classification V Experiments V-A Single-phase disturbance detection V-B Three-phase fault detection VI Conclusions References License: CC BY 4.0 arXiv:2607.20817v1 [cs.SD] 23 Jul 2026 Spectrogram-Based Joint Detection, Localization, and Classification of Events in Continuously Recorded IBR Waveforms Shivanshu Tripathi, Maziar Raissi, and Hamed Mohsenian-Rad S. Tripathi, and H. Mohsenian-Rad are with the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, and M. Raissi is with the Department of Mathematics at the University of California, Riverside, { strip008 , maziarr , hamedrad}@ucr.edu . Abstract Continuously recorded high-resolution waveform measurements provide rich information about fast power system dynamics. However, they require automated methods to identify events. This problem is addressed by developing a spectrogram-based framework to jointly detect, localize, and classify events in real-world continuously recorded waveforms at the terminal of an Inverter-Based Resource. We recast this problem as a temporal object detection problem on spectrogram images, as they capture the transient and harmonic signatures more explicitly than in raw waveform data. Each time-series waveform is transformed using the short-time Fourier transform, and the resulting per-channel spectrograms are stacked as a tensor for event detection. We benchmark this method against a detector operating directly on raw time-series measurements. Experiments on single-phase disturbances and three-phase faults demonstrate that the proposed spectrogram method consistently improves event detection, localization, and classification over the raw waveform baseline. Keywords: Continuously recorded waveforms, inverter-based resources, event detection, spectrogram, deep learning. I Introduction Modern power systems are going through a rapid transition driven by the growing integration of inverter-based resources (IBRs), renewables, and power-electronic loads. These resources introduce fast transients as well as harmonic emissions. Typical events include switching, oscillations, and incipient faults. These events are difficult to analyze, yet detecting them is valuable, as they can reveal early fault detection and help prevent permanent damage. Such dynamics can be captured by the Waveform Measurement Unit (WMU), which records voltage and current waveforms as continuous samples at kilohertz rates [ 11 ] . A practical monitoring system answers three questions: whether an event is present (detection), when it begins and ends (localization), and what type it is (classification). Answering these questions is challenging for two reasons. First, events are vastly outnumbered by normal operation, creating severe class imbalance. Second, many of these event signatures are usually small in magnitude. Thus, the harmonic and transient spectral content that distinguishes an event may remain implicit in the time-series representation. To bridge this gap, this paper proposes a spectrogram-based event detector. Each waveform channel is transformed into the time-frequency domain, so that the harmonic and transient components appear as explicit visual features rather than being latent in the raw time-series measurements. Related Work: Existing works for power system event detection can be broadly categorized into two classes: time-series based methods and frequency-based methods. The time-series methods flag an event when the signal amplitude departs from its expected behavior. These approaches monitor the RMS value or the peak magnitude of voltage and current, and declare an event when a threshold is exceeded [ 12 , 3 ] . Such rules are simple and widely used in power quality monitoring. However, events whose signatures are subtle in magnitude, such as incipient faults or low-level oscillations, are missed as noise [ 6 , 7 ] . In contrast, frequency-based methods leverage the spectral content of the waveform. The Fourier transform captures harmonic and inter-harmonic components, but discards the time information needed for localization. Time-frequency representations recover this timing. The STFT, wavelet transform, S S -transform and Hilbert transform have been used in power-quality analysis [ 16 , 5 , 4 , 17 ] . These representations make transient and harmonic signatures explicit and can capture events that remain invisible to purely amplitude-based schemes [ 2 ] . Recent work couples time-frequency features with learning-based classifiers, ranging from support vector machines [ 1 ] and decision trees [ 8 ] to convolutional neural networks applied directly to time-frequency images [ 18 ] . Most existing learning-based schemes treat detection, localization, and classification as separate stages. In contrast, we address all three tasks jointly. The proposed approach falls within the frequency-based category. Our formulation is inspired by object detection in computer vision, where single-stage detectors such as YOLO [ 13 ] and SSD [ 9 ] regress bounding boxes together with class labels and confidence scores, avoiding the region-proposal stage of two-stage detectors [ 14 ] . A similar philosophy underlies sound event detection, where events are localized in time on audio spectrograms [ 10 ] . Building on these ideas, we adopt an encoder-decoder U-Net architecture [ 15 ] that scores every temporal window for event presence and class label. Contributions. The main contributions of the paper are as follows. First, we recast the detection, temporal localization, and classification of events as a single temporal object-detection problem on spectrogram images. Second, we introduce an STFT-based log-spectrogram tensor representation that maps multi-channel waveform measurements into a form that can be used for image-based object detection. Third, we develop a U-Net detector that regresses normalized temporal bounding boxes together with a confidence score and a class label. Finally, we evaluate the proposed framework against a raw time-series baseline on both single-phase and three-phase event detection tasks. II Problem Formulation We consider the problem of detecting events in time-synchronized waveforms, localizing each event in time, and identifying its label directly from the raw waveforms. Let X j ∈ ℝ T j × C X_{j}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T_{j}\\times C} denote the j j -th waveform record in the dataset, X j = [ x j ​ [ 0 ] , … , x j ​ [ T j − 1 ] ] ⊤ ∈ ℝ T j × C , X_{j}=\\big[\\,x_{j}[0],\\dots,x_{j}[T_{j}-1]\\,\\big]^{\\!\\top}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T_{j}\\times C}, (1) where T j T_{j} is the number of samples in the record and C C is the number of channels. For a system with P P phases, each sample t ∈ { 0 , … , T j − 1 } t\\in\\{0,\\dots,T_{j}-1\\} stacks the per-phase voltage and current measurements, x j ​ [ t ] = ( v 1 ​ [ t ] , … , v P ​ [ t ] , i 1 ​ [ t ] , … , i P ​ [ t ] ) ⊤ ∈ ℝ C , C = 2 ​ P , x_{j}[t]=\\big(v_{1}[t],\\dots,v_{P}[t],\\,i_{1}[t],\\dots,i_{P}[t]\\big)^{\\!\\top}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{C},~~C=2P, so that the single-phase case corresponds to P = 1 P=1 ( C = 2 C=2 ) and the three-phase case to P = 3 P=3 ( C = 6 C=6 ). A record may contain one or more events. Each record is annotated with a set of E j E_{j} events, 𝒜 j = { ( I j , m , y j , m ) } m = 1 E j , \\mathcal{A}_{j}=\\big\\{\\,(I_{j,m},\\,y_{j,m})\\,\\big\\}_{m=1}^{E_{j}}, (2) where I j , m = [ s j , m , e j , m ] I_{j,m}=[\\,s_{j,m},\\,e_{j,m}\\,] , with 0 ≤ s j , m ≤ e j , m ≤ T j − 1 0\\leq s_{j,m}\\leq e_{j,m}\\leq T_{j}-1 , is the temporal interval (onset and offset samples) of the m m -th event, and y j , m ∈ 𝒴 y_{j,m}\\in\\mathcal{Y} is its class label. The label set 𝒴 = { 1 , … , K } \\mathcal{Y}=\\{\\,1,\\dots,K\\,\\} has K K event classes. Given a waveform record X X of length T T , our objective is to jointly detect, temporally localize, and classify the events it contains. We cast this as learning a detector f θ : ℝ T × C → 𝒟 f_{\\theta}:\\ \\mathbb{R}^{T\\times C}\\to\\mathcal{D} , parameterized by θ \\theta , that maps a record to an element of the space 𝒟 \\mathcal{D} of scored detection sets. Concretely, the detector returns a set of N ^ \\hat{N} candidate detections, f θ ​ ( ⋅ ) = { ( b ^ k , p ^ k , y ^ k ) } k = 1 N ^ , f_{\\theta}(\\cdot)=\\big\\{\\,(\\hat{b}_{k},\\ \\hat{p}_{k},\\ \\hat{y}_{k})\\,\\big\\}_{k=1}^{\\hat{N}}, (3) where b ^ k = [ s ^ k , e ^ k ] \\hat{b}_{k}=[\\,\\hat{s}_{k},\\,\\hat{e}_{k}\\,] is a predicted event interval, p ^ k ∈ [ 0 , 1 ] \\hat{p}_{k}\\in[0,1] is the confidence score of an event present in b ^ k \\hat{b}_{k} , and y ^ k ∈ 𝒴 \\hat{y}_{k}\\in\\mathcal{Y} is the predicted event class. A predicted detection is deemed correct when its temporal intersection-over-union (IoU) with a ground-truth interval of the same class meets or exceeds a preset threshold ( α ) (\\alpha) at inference. III Spectrogram Image Construction and Training Dataset In this section, we describe how each waveform record is mapped to a time-frequency spectrogram image and how the sample-level annotations in the waveform are converted into normalized temporal boxes used for training. III-A Spectrogram Image The STFT slides a short analysis window across each channel of the record. Each channel waveform is divided into short, overlapping frames of L L samples, where frame m m begins at sample m ​ H mH and the hop H = ( 1 − p / 100 ) ​ L H=(1-p/100)L is set by p % p\\% overlap between consecutive frames. For channel c c , the frame m m is the vector X c m ∈ ℝ L X_{c}^{\\,m}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{L} defined as X c m ​ [ n ] = x c ​ [ n + m ​ H ] , n = 0 , … , L − 1 , X_{c}^{\\,m}[n]=x_{c}[\\,n+mH\\,],\\qquad n=0,\\dots,L-1, (4) where x c ​ [ ⋅ ] x_{c}[\\cdot] denotes the c c -th channel of the record. A record of length T j T_{j} yields M j = ⌊ ( T j − L ) / H ⌋ + 1 M_{j}=\\big\\lfloor(T_{j}-L)/H\\big\\rfloor+1 frames, indexed m = 0 , … , M j − 1 m=0,\\dots,M_{j}-1 . Each frame in ( 4 ) is tapered by a smooth Hamming window g ​ [ n ] g[n] to limit spectral leakage and is mapped to a Q Q -point discrete Fourier transform (DFT), X ~ c m ​ ( f ) = ∑ n = 0 L − 1 g ​ [ n ] ​ X c m ​ [ n ] ​ e − ȷ ​ 2 ​ π ​ f ​ n / Q , f = 1 , … , Q − 1 , \\tilde{X}_{c}^{\\,m}(f)=\\sum_{n=0}^{L-1}g[n]\\,X_{c}^{\\,m}[n]\\,e^{-\\jmath 2\\pi fn/Q},\\quad f=1,\\dots,Q-1, (5) with Q ≥ L Q\\geq L . The corresponding power spectrum is P c m ​ ( f ) = 1 L ​ | X ~ c m ​ ( f ) | 2 . P_{c}^{\\,m}(f)=\\tfrac{1}{L}\\,\\big|\\tilde{X}_{c}^{\\,m}(f)\\big|^{2}. (6) Two further steps turn ( 6 ) into a suitable representation for detection. First, the diagnostic content is concentrated in the low-order harmonics, so of the Q Q DFT bins we retain only the F F lowest-frequency bins. The discarded bins carry mostly noise, and removing them reduces the input size and the computation. Second, the fundamental dominates the spectrum by several orders of magnitude; therefore, a logarithmic compression rescales faint harmonics so that they remain visible alongside the much stronger fundamental, S ~ c m ​ ( f ) = log ⁡ ( 1 + P c m ​ ( f ) ) , f = 1 , … , F . \\tilde{S}_{c}^{\\,m}(f)=\\log\\!\\big(1+P_{c}^{\\,m}(f)\\big),\\qquad f=1,\\dots,F. (7) Collecting ( 7 ) over all frames of a waveform yields the per-channel log-spectrogram, S c ∈ ℝ M j × F , [ S c ] m , f = S ~ c m ​ ( f ) . S_{c}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M_{j}\\times F},\\qquad\\big[S_{c}\\big]_{m,f}=\\tilde{S}_{c}^{\\,m}(f). (8) Finally, stacking ( 8 ) over the channel set 𝒞 \\mathcal{C} , produces a tensor, 𝐙 j = stack c ∈ 𝒞 ( S c ) ∈ ℝ M j × F × C , [ 𝐙 j ] m , f , c = S ~ c m ​ ( f ) , \\mathbf{Z}_{j}=\\operatorname*{stack}_{c\\in\\mathcal{C}}\\big(S_{c}\\big)\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M_{j}\\times F\\times C},\\quad\\big[\\mathbf{Z}_{j}\\big]_{m,f,c}=\\tilde{S}_{c}^{\\,m}(f), (9) which is the multi-channel spectrogram scene presented to the detector. Fig. 1 illustrates this construction. Figure 1: The figure shows the construction of the spectrogram tensor Z j Z_{j} used as training data. Panel (a) shows a STFT pipeline, illustrated on the phase voltage v a v_{a} . The waveform x ​ ( t ) x(t) is split into overlapping L L -sample frames at hop H H , each tapered by a Hamming window g g and mapped to its log-power spectrogram (Eqs. ( 4 )–( 7 )). Placing these vectors side by side for all m = 0 , … , M j − 1 m=0,\\dots,M_{j}-1 assembles the per-channel log-spectrogram S c S_{c} of Eq. ( 8 ). Panel (b) shows the per-channel log-spectrograms S c ∈ ℝ M j × F S_{c}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M_{j}\\times F} (Eq. ( 8 )) of all six channels of three-phase, stacked along the channel axis into the tensor 𝐙 j ∈ ℝ M j × F × 6 \\mathbf{Z}_{j}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M_{j}\\times F\\times 6} (Eq. ( 9 )), the input to the detector. III-B Training Dataset The frame m m spans samples [ m ​ H , m ​ H + L − 1 ] [mH,\\,mH+L-1] , so it overlaps the event if and only if m ​ H ≤ e mH\\leq e and m ​ H + L − 1 ≥ s mH+L-1\\geq s . Solving these two inequalities yields the event frame span, m s = ⌈ s − L + 1 H ⌉ , m e = ⌊ e H ⌋ . m_{s}=\\Big\\lceil\\tfrac{s-L+1}{H}\\Big\\rceil,\\qquad m_{e}=\\Big\\lfloor\\tfrac{e}{H}\\Big\\rfloor. (10) Since the detector localizes the event along the time-axis, the ground-truth fault box reduces to the frame interval ( m s , m e ) \\big(m_{s},\\,m_{e}\\big) . We express it in normalized form: b = ( t c , w t ) ∈ [ 0 , 1 ] 2 , t c = m s + m e 2 ​ M j , w t = m e − m s M j , b\\!=\\!\\big(t_{c},w_{t}\\big)\\in[0,1]^{2},\\quad t_{c}\\!=\\!\\frac{m_{s}+m_{e}}{2M_{j}},\\quad w_{t}\\!=\\!\\frac{m_{e}-m_{s}}{M_{j}}, (11) and paired with the class label y j ∈ 𝒴 y_{j}\\in\\mathcal{Y} . Normalizing by the number of frames M j M_{j} makes the box coordinates independent of the record length and the chosen hop. The training set is then the collection of spectrogram scenes paired with their annotations 𝒟 = { ( 𝐙 j , { ( b j , m , y j , m ) } m = 1 E j ) } j , \\mathcal{D}=\\Big\\{\\,\\big(\\mathbf{Z}_{j},\\;\\{(b_{j,m},y_{j,m})\\}_{m=1}^{E_{j}}\\big)\\,\\Big\\}_{j}, (12) where ( b j , m , y j , m ) (b_{j,m},y_{j,m}) denotes the normalized box label pair of the m m -th event of record j j , so that it contains a box label pair per event and E j = 0 E_{j}=0 for records without events. IV Fault Detection Framework We now describe the detector that operates on the spectrogram scenes of Section III . Let f θ f_{\\theta} denote the U-Net detector that maps a scene 𝐙 j \\mathbf{Z}_{j} to a set of N ^ \\hat{N} candidate detections, f θ ​ ( 𝐙 j ) = { ( b ^ k , p ^ k , y ^ k ) } k = 1 N ^ , f_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{Z}_{j})=\\big\\{(\\hat{b}_{k},\\hat{p}_{k},\\hat{y}_{k})\\big\\}_{k=1}^{\\hat{N}}, (13) where b ^ k = ( t ^ c , w ^ t ) ∈ [ 0 , 1 ] 2 \\hat{b}_{k}=(\\hat{t}_{c},\\hat{w}_{t})\\in[0,1]^{2} is a predicted temporal box in normalized coordinates of ( 11 ), p ^ k ∈ [ 0 , 1 ] \\hat{p}_{k}\\in[0,1] its confidence score, and y ^ k \\hat{y}_{k} its predicted class. Inverting the normalization in ( 11 ) for a predicted event box b ^ = ( t ^ c , w ^ t ) \\hat{b}=(\\hat{t}_{c},\\hat{w}_{t}) gives the frame interval: m ^ s = ⌊ M j ​ ( t ^ c − w ^ t 2 ) ⌋ , m ^ e = ⌈ M j ​ ( t ^ c + w ^ t 2 ) ⌉ , \\hat{m}_{s}=\\Big\\lfloor M_{j}\\big(\\hat{t}_{c}-\\tfrac{\\hat{w}_{t}}{2}\\big)\\Big\\rfloor,\\qquad\\hat{m}_{e}=\\Big\\lceil M_{j}\\big(\\hat{t}_{c}+\\tfrac{\\hat{w}_{t}}{2}\\big)\\Big\\rceil, (14) giving estimated event interval [ s ^ , e ^ ] = [ m ^ s ​ H , m ^ e ​ H + L − 1 ] [\\hat{s},\\hat{e}]=[\\hat{m}_{s}H,\\hat{m}_{e}H+L-1] . IV-A Training the U-Net Detector We train the network for detection and classification simultaneously. The detection objective applies to every temporal window and uses a class-weighted cross-entropy loss function, assigning a higher weight to event windows to compensate for their scarcity relative to normal operation. The classification objective applies only to event-containing windows and uses cross-entropy loss over the event classes. The overall objective is: ℒ = ℒ detection + ℒ classification \\mathcal{L}=\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{detection}}+\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{classification}} . The network learns to assign each window a confidence score, i.e., the probability that an event is present in that window. IV-B Selecting Candidates via the Confidence Threshold τ \\tau At inference, among the N ^ \\hat{N} candidates in ( 13 ) we retain those whose confidence satisfies p ^ k ≥ τ \\hat{p}_{k}\\geq\\tau . If no candidate survives, the scene is declared event-free. The threshold τ \\tau is chosen by the validation set. We compute the precision and recall for each τ \\tau , and select the value that maximizes their F ​ 1 F1 score. The selected τ \\tau is then fixed for all test records. IV-C Evaluation metrics We consider different evaluation metrics for detection, localization, and classification: Localization It is evaluated using intersection-over-union (IoU) between a predicted b ^ \\hat{b} and a true interval b b , IoU ​ ( b ^ , b ) = | b ^ ∩ b | | b ^ ∪ b | , \\mathrm{IoU}(\\hat{b},b)=\\frac{|\\hat{b}\\cap b|}{|\\hat{b}\\cup b|}, (15) where | ⋅ | |\\cdot| denotes the length of the interval. We report the IoU of the matched detections, averaged over the test events. Detection At a fixed overlap threshold α \\alpha , a predicted interval counts as a true positive (TP) if IoU ​ ( b ^ , b ) ≥ α \\mathrm{IoU}(\\hat{b},b)\\geq\\alpha ; any other predicted interval is a false positive (FP), and a ground-truth event with no matching prediction is a false negative (FN). Then, precision and recall are P = TP TP + FP , R = TP TP + FN . P=\\frac{\\mathrm{TP}}{\\mathrm{TP}+\\mathrm{FP}},\\qquad R=\\frac{\\mathrm{TP}}{\\mathrm{TP}+\\mathrm{FN}}. (16) Varying the confidence threshold τ \\tau at fixed α \\alpha traces a precision-recall curve. We define the average precision as AP = ∑ n ( R n + 1 − R n ) ​ P interp ​ ( R n + 1 ) , P interp ​ ( R ) = max R ~ ≥ R ⁡ P ​ ( R ~ ) , \\displaystyle\\begin{aligned} &\\mathrm{AP}=\\sum_{n}\\big(R_{n+1}-R_{n}\\big)\\,P_{\\mathrm{interp}}(R_{n+1}),\\\\ &P_{\\mathrm{interp}}(R)=\\max_{\\tilde{R}\\geq R}P(\\tilde{R}),\\end{aligned} (17) i.e., the area under the interpolated precision-recall curve. With multiple event classes, we report the mean average precision mAP = 1 | 𝒴 | ​ ∑ i ∈ 𝒴 AP i \\mathrm{mAP}=\\tfrac{1}{|\\mathcal{Y}|}\\sum_{i\\in\\mathcal{Y}}\\mathrm{AP}_{i} . We also report mAP [ .5 : .95 ] \\mathrm{mAP}_{[.5:.95]} , obtained by averaging AP over the IoU thresholds α ∈ { 0.50 , 0.55 , … , 0.95 } \\alpha\\in\\{0.50,0.55,\\dots,0.95\\} . Classification The event type accuracy is computed on the true-positive detections. Among the correctly localized events, we report the fraction assigned the correct class label. TABLE I: Single-phase disturbance detection on the held-out test day ( 40 40 s of data), comparing the spectrogram U-Net-2D (ours) with the raw time-series U-Net-1D baseline across four STFT overlaps. Performance improves as the hop shrinks. Detection Localization Class. Representation Overlap (hop) AP@0.5 AP@0.7 mAP [.5:.95] Recall@0.5 IoU type accuracy time-series (baseline) — 0.650 0.550 0.650 0.831 0.654 0.454 spectrogram (ours) 0 % 0\\% ( H = 64 H{=}64 ) 0.949 0.705 0.950 0.796 0.974 0.557 spectrogram (ours) 25 % 25\\% ( H = 48 H{=}48 ) 0.975 0.891 