{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1784874897875", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "我现在已经有了足够的事实锚点。让我再尝试通过 WebFetch 获取“Eventness”论文的摘要（因为 Bash/curl 可以使用），以确认其与本文的关系，并检查引用 [18]（即直接应用于时频图像的 CNN 论文）。"}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "718a8c7f-8b52-4dd6-87a7-df8e48076344", "uuid": "9507809c-d931-4b5d-988a-e69a9009e450"}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1784874897875", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-a69850fb415c996d", "name": "Bash", "input": {"command": "curl -sL \"https://arxiv.org/abs/1712.09668\" 2>&1 | python3 -c \"\nimport sys, re, html\nraw = sys.stdin.read()\n# Extract abstract\nm = re.search(r'<blockquote class=\\\"abstract[^>]*>.*?<span class=\\\"descriptor\\\">Abstract:</span>\\s*(.*?)</blockquote>', raw, re.DOTALL)\nif m:\n    text = re.sub(r'<[^>]+>', '', m.group(1))\n    text = html.unescape(text).strip()\n    print('ABSTRACT:', text[:2000])\nelse:\n    # fallback\n    m2 = re.search(r'Abstract:\\s*(.*?)(?:</blockquote>|<blockquote)', raw, re.DOTALL)\n    if m2:\n        text = re.sub(r'<[^>]+>', '', m2.group(1))\n        print('ABSTRACT:', html.unescape(text).strip()[:2000])\n    else:\n        print('NO ABSTRACT FOUND')\n\" 2>&1 | head -20", "description": "Fetch Eventness paper abstract"}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "718a8c7f-8b52-4dd6-87a7-df8e48076344", "uuid": "07c6d679-e58d-4df5-a05b-c3c621bb0718"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a69850fb415c996d", "type": "tool_result", "content": "ABSTRACT: In this paper, we introduce the concept of Eventness for audio event detection, which can, in part, be thought of as an analogue to Objectness from computer vision. The key observation behind the eventness concept is that audio events reveal themselves as 2-dimensional time-frequency patterns with specific textures and geometric structures in spectrograms. These time-frequency patterns can then be viewed analogously to objects occurring in natural images (with the exception that scaling and rotation invariance properties do not apply). With this key observation in mind, we pose the problem of detecting monophonic or polyphonic audio events as an equivalent visual object(s) detection problem under partial occlusion and clutter in spectrograms. We adapt a state-of-the-art visual object detection model to evaluate the audio event detection task on publicly available datasets. The proposed network has comparable results with a state-of-the-art baseline and is more robust on minority events. Provided large-scale datasets, we hope that our proposed conceptual model of eventness will be beneficial to the audio signal processing community towards improving performance of audio event detection.", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "718a8c7f-8b52-4dd6-87a7-df8e48076344", "uuid": "87eec23e-e0e5-4b0e-a468-d18c6e544d75", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T06:35:45.476Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "ABSTRACT: In this paper, we introduce the concept of Eventness for audio event detection, which can, in part, be thought of as an analogue to Objectness from computer vision. The key observation behind the eventness concept is that audio events reveal themselves as 2-dimensional time-frequency patterns with specific textures and geometric structures in spectrograms. These time-frequency patterns can then be viewed analogously to objects occurring in natural images (with the exception that scaling and rotation invariance properties do not apply). With this key observation in mind, we pose the problem of detecting monophonic or polyphonic audio events as an equivalent visual object(s) detection problem under partial occlusion and clutter in spectrograms. We adapt a state-of-the-art visual object detection model to evaluate the audio event detection task on publicly available datasets. The proposed network has comparable results with a state-of-the-art baseline and is more robust on minority events. Provided large-scale datasets, we hope that our proposed conceptual model of eventness will be beneficial to the audio signal processing community towards improving performance of audio event detection.", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1784874964003", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "这证实了关键的发现。现在我已经拥有进行完整审查所需的所有事实锚点：\n\n**关键发现：**\n1. **全文已获取**：通过 arXiv HTML（所有章节：I-VI + 参考文献 + 表格 I-II）\n2. **Eventness (arXiv:1712.09668, 2017)**：在音频领域提出了相同的核心思路——“将音频事件检测视为频谱图上的视觉目标检测问题”。该论文甚至引用了 YOLO/SSD。这是所提方法直接的跨领域先驱。\n3. **电力系统波形 CNN 工作已存在**（通过 exa 搜索找到）：包括“Synchro-Waveform-Based Event Identification Using Multi-Task Time-Frequency Transform Networks” (OSTI)，以及“Complementary Feature Extractions for Event Identification in Power Systems Using Multi-Channel CNN” (MDPI Energies)。\n4. **引用 [18]**：该论文承认了“直接应用于时频图像的 CNN”先前工作的存在，但将其表征为“将检测、定位和分类视为独立的阶段”——这构成了其关于联合处理的新颖性主张。\n5. **数据集**：真实世界的 IBR 终端波形（单相：6 天 × 40 秒；三相：200 条记录）。规模非常小。\n6. **代码/数据**：声明已开源 (GitHub 链接)。\n7. **基线**：仅有 U-Net-1D（原始时间序列）与 U-Net-2D（频谱图）的对比——架构相同，仅输入表示不同。这种受控比较在识别公理上是好的，但缺少外部 SOTA 基线。\n\n现在我将输出完整的结构化审查报告。"}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "718a8c7f-8b52-4dd6-87a7-df8e48076344", "uuid": "4d30d6a5-439a-430a-a64d-8637cb7d778e"}
